      "result": {
        "original_header": "Input:",
        "type": "Text_excerpt",
        "value": "The default behaviour expects fastq files from a Nextera Mate-Pair library kit in reverse-forward orientation.\n \n"
      },
      "source": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sequencing/NxTrim/master/README.md",
      "technique": "supervised_classification"
    },
    {
      "confidence": 0.9149422254452283,
      "result": {
        "original_header": "Output:",
        "type": "Text_excerpt",
        "value": "* mp: read pairs that are large insert-size mate-pairs, both mates will be reverse-complemented by nxtrim (from RF to FR) unless `--rf` commandline option is used\n* pe: read pairs that are short insert-size paired-end reads due to the junction adapter occurring early in a read\n* se: single reads (reads having no R1 or R2 counterpart)\n* unknown: a library of read-pairs that are mostly large-insert mate-pair, but possibly contain a small proportion of paired end contaminants \nOutput is reverse-complemented such that the resulting reads will be in forward-reverse orientation.\n \n"
      },
      "source": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sequencing/NxTrim/master/README.md",
      "technique": "supervised_classification"
    },
    {
      "confidence": 0.9046139533814023,
      "result": {
        "original_header": "Options:",
        "type": "Text_excerpt",
        "value": "If you wish to generate pure mate-pair libraries (say for scaffolding), you can use the `--justmp` flag.  This will only generate the unknown and mp libraries.  Reads with a junction adapter occurring < minlength bp before the start will be completely N masked. \nIf you wish to preserve mate-pair libraries whenever possible, the `--preservemp` flag may be useful.  This will always keep the mate-pair library *unless* a read generated would be < minlength, in which case it will generate a PE. \nYou can trade specificity/sensitivity of junction adapter detection with the `--similarity` flag (1 - proportion of bp differences allowed for match) and the `--minoverlap` flag (minimum #bp considered on the ends of reads to match with the Nextera junction adapter).  The defaults were well suited to bacteria in our testing. \nYou can turn on a more aggressive search for junction adapters with `--aggressive`. [Some notes on how we detect adapters are here](https://github.com/sequencing/NxTrim/blob/master/docs/adapter_matching.md).\n \n"
      },
      "source": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/sequencing/NxTrim/master/README.md",
      "technique": "supervised_classification"
    },
